    "Three species are widely used: **Echinacea purpurea** (the most common and easiest to grow), **Echinacea angustifolia**, and **Echinacea pallida**. The roots and aerial parts (leaves, flowers) are all used. Its primary immune-stimulating effects are attributed to compounds called **alkylamides and polysaccharides**, which are thought to stimulate white blood cell production and enhance the body's natural defense mechanisms.",
    dailyLifeUses:
    "The most common daily use is taking a tincture, capsule, or tea at the **first sign of a cold or flu** to potentially lessen the severity and duration of the illness. It is typically taken for short periods (7-10 days) rather than continuously. Topically, creams and salves containing Echinacea are used to help heal minor wounds, skin abrasions, and boils due to its mild antibacterial properties.",
    precaution:
    "Individuals with **autoimmune disorders** (such as lupus, multiple sclerosis, or rheumatoid arthritis) or progressive systemic diseases should consult a physician before using Echinacea, as it is an immune stimulant. It should also be avoided by people with allergies to the daisy family (Asteraceae). While generally safe for short-term use, the long-term safety of continuous, high-dose use is less established.",
